§ea-The subjunctive is used, too, in relative clauses, where the writer intends to convey the idea of an action frequently repeated. This rule is, however, in all probability, identical with one of the preceding, because the relative does not in these cases refer definitely to any one case, but to all which might have taken place, which not being always known, renders the relative clause in a measure hypothetical. Thus, eo postquam Cesar pervenit, obsides, arma, servos, qui ad eos persa pissea t, poposcit, Caes. B. G. i. 27.
